{"version": 2, "width": 120, "height": 46, "timestamp": 1781760922, "idle_time_limit": 2.0, "env": {"SHELL": "/bin/bash", "TERM": "tmux-256color"}, "title": "Aqueduct — an LLM buys 15 exoplanet rows it cannot answer from memory (MPP on Tempo)"}
[0.323112, "o", "\u001b[1G\u001b[0K⠙"]
[0.337005, "o", "\u001b[1G\u001b[0K"]
[2.834084, "o", "\u001b[1m\r\n  AQUEDUCT — an LLM buys specific data from a big Tap (via the aqueduct skill)\r\n\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.834211, "o", "  \u001b[2mdataset:\u001b[0m NASA exoplanet archive (real)   \u001b[2mquestion:\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.83427, "o", "  \u001b[1mList the 15 Earth-sized exoplanets (radius 0.8–1.5 Earth radii) closest to Earth. For each, give its name, distance (pc), radius, equilibrium temperature, discovery method, and discovery year.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[2.834476, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  0  WITHOUT AQUEDUCT — the agent answers from memory alone (no data)\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.099174, "o", "  \u001b[2mI cannot reliably produce a precise 15-row table (distance, radius, equilibrium temperature, method, year) from memory without fabricating values, so treat specific numbers as low-to-moderate confidence. The closest well-established Earth-sized (~0.8–1.5 R⊕) candidates by distance are roughly: Proxima Centauri b (~1.30 pc), Barnard's Star b (~1.83 pc), the GJ 1061 planets b/c/d (~3.7 pc), Teegarden's Star b/c (~3.8 pc), GJ 1002 b/c (~4.8 pc), Ross 128 b (~3.4 pc), Wolf 1069 b (~9.6 pc), GJ 273 b (Luyten's Star, ~3.8 pc), and GJ 357 b (~9.4 pc)—nearly all found via radial velocity (most 2016–2023), except GJ 357 b (transit, 2019). For exact radii and equilibrium temperatures I'd recommend the NASA Exoplanet Archive, as my memorized figures here are not trustworthy enough to tabulate confidently.\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.262602, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  1  SERVE — compile the exoplanet archive into a Tap and run it\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.819805, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m server wallet \u001b[2m(pre-funded)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[21.845658, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m \u001b[1m1,529 planets\u001b[0m live on http://localhost:8700  \u001b[2m(0.0001 pathUSD/row)\u001b[0m\r\n\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  2  DISCOVER — the agent reads the Tap's terms for free (skill: --schema)\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[25.137141, "o", "  \u001b[2mcolumns:\u001b[0m name:string  host_star:string  discovery_year:integer  method:string  distance_pc:number  period_days:number  radius_earth:number  mass_earth:number  eq_temp_k:integer\r\n"]
[25.137209, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  3  PLAN — the LLM translates the question into a paid query\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[31.058601, "o", "  \u001b[2mLLM query →\u001b[0m \u001b[36m{\"select\":[\"name\",\"distance_pc\",\"radius_earth\",\"eq_temp_k\",\"method\",\"discovery_year\"],\"filters\":[{\"field\":\"radius_earth\",\"op\":\"gte\",\"value\":0.8},{\"field\":\"radius_earth\",\"op\":\"lte\",\"value\":1.5}],\"sort\":[{\"field\":\"distance_pc\",\"dir\":\"asc\"}],\"limit\":15}\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[31.058694, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  4  BUY — the agent pays per row over an MPP session (skill: paid query)\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[31.229743, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m agent wallet \u001b[2m(pre-funded)\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[36.853084, "o", "  \u001b[32m✓\u001b[0m bought \u001b[1m15 rows\u001b[0m for \u001b[1m0.0015 pathUSD\u001b[0m  \u001b[2msettled 0x4b414f00030cae77…\u001b[0m\r\n      \u001b[2mhttps://explore.testnet.tempo.xyz/tx/0x4b414f00030cae77ed9efba4fdb81f1f5c511b9514ad374b2ef114d3367cad6e\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[36.853166, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  5  ANSWER — the LLM answers from only the rows it bought\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[52.628521, "o", "  | Name | Distance (pc) | Radius (R⊕) | Eq. Temp (K) | Method | Year |\r\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\r\n| HD 219134 f | 6.53 | 1.31 | 523 | Radial Velocity | 2015 |\r\n| LTT 1445 A c | 6.87 | 1.15 | 508 | Transit | 2022 |\r\n| LTT 1445 A b | 6.87 | 1.34 | 431 | Transit | 2019 |\r\n| GJ 486 b | 8.07 | 1.29 | 696 | Radial Velocity | 2021 |\r\n| GJ 357 b | 9.44 | 1.20 | 518 | Transit | 2019 |\r\n| HD 260655 b | 10.01 | 1.24 | 709 | Transit | 2022 |\r\n| L 98-59 b | 10.62 | 0.84 | 620 | Transit | 2019 |\r\n| L 98-59 c | 10.62 | 1.33 | 526 | Transit | 2019 |\r\n| GJ 806 b | 12.04 | 1.33 | 940 | Transit | 2023 |\r\n| LHS 475 b | 12.48 | 0.99 | 586 | Transit | 2023 |\r\n| GJ 1132 b | 12.61 | 1.19 | 584 | Transit | 2015 |\r\n| HD 101581 c | 12.78 | 0.99 | 747 | Transit | 2025 |\r\n| HD 101581 b | 12.78 | 0.96 | 834 | Transit | 2025 |\r\n| TOI-540 b | 14.00 | 0.90 | 611 | Transit | 2020 |\r\n| LHS 3844 b | 14.88 | 1.29 | 816 | Transit | 2019 |\r\n\r\n**Highlights:**\r\n\r\n- **HD 219134 f** is the closest at 6.53 pc and the only radial-velocity discovery in the upper half of the list; nearly all others were found by transit.\r\n- **LTT 1445 A** hosts two qualifying planets (b and c) at 6.87 pc, making it the nearest multi-planet system here and a prime atmospheric-characterization target.\r\n- **L 98-59 b** is the smallest at 0.84 R⊕, while **GJ 806 b** is the hottest at 940 K — bracketing the temperature and size range of the sample.\r\n"]
[52.628614, "o", "\r\n\u001b[1m\u001b[36m  6  THE DIFFERENCE\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\r\n  \u001b[2mwithout Aqueduct:\u001b[0m a guess from training memory — plausible, unverifiable, stale\r\n  \u001b[2mwith Aqueduct:\u001b[0m    15 exact rows from the live archive, 0.0015 pathUSD, settled on-chain — verifiable + current\r\n"]
[52.629056, "o", "\u001b[32m\u001b[1m\r\n  ✓ DONE — answered from 15 paid rows, never touching the other 1,514.\r\n\u001b[0m\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[52.682231, "o", "\u001b[1G\u001b[0K⠙"]
